{"/service/ndnp/az/batch_az_apachetrout_ver01/data/sn85032923/00211105653/1913080601/0269.xml":{"full_text":"Weekly\nRNAL-Ml\nPIONEER PAPER OF ARIZONA.\nPRESCOTT, ARIZONA, WEWESDAY MORNING,. AUGUST 6, 1913.\nFIFTIETH YEAR.\nJmJ\nJ3ids Bankers\nTo Conference\nMcAdoo and Financiers Will Discuss\nfir\nDistribution of (mey to Facilitate\nTLe MovemeSt of Crops\nBy Associated Press.\nWASHINGTON, D. C, Aug.'.4.\nRepresentative bankers of fiftynine\nlarge cities in the agricultural regions\nof the South, the Middle: WesV and\nthe Pacific Coast have Veen invited\nby Secretary M'cAdoo to tdme to\nWashington to confer'--wjfh the\nTreasury Department TegaYding the\ndistribution of fifty mjfifon dollars\nof government funds ibout to be\ndeposited in National banks in those\nsections to facilitate the marketing\nand movement of crops. This step\nis designed to give the Secretary\nfirst-hand information about the\nspecific relative needs of each farm\ning district.\nIt has been decided \"tentatively to\nplace deposits in the fifty-nine cities\nrepresented at the conference. In\nvitations wre telegraphed to the prcs\nidents'of clearing house associations\nin cachpf tlij, cities, asking them to\nsend regresentojiyes and committees.\nThe confjence with representatives\nof the southerft .cities is st for August\nof the southetgrfifjes is set for August\n8th and the PJjfcfic Coast on August\n14th. Among tinjuties invited were\nLos Angeles and Denver.\nLEAD.\nNEW YORK, August 4. Lead\n$4.40 to $4.50.\nNEW\n59H. 1\nSILVER.\nYORK, August 4. Silver\nOVER iPORCH\nWALKS TO HIS\nDEATH\nHEPLA POVITICS' IN Rioting Brings\nJOHN O'DONEL INSTANT\nLY KILLED AT PIONEERS\nHOME AT EARLY HOUR\nTHIS MORNING\niirei kiii(;\n\"of b&fcen\nes. T\nBOTH SIDES TO TO LAUNCH FAIR\nTRY HAND AT\nWALL\nWASHINGTON, D. C, Aug. 4.\nInvestigation of the activities of\nMartin M. Mulhall for the National\nAssociation of Manufacturers wilt oc\ncupy the committee on both sides\nof the capitol tomorrow for the first\n-time since the lobbyist made his\nstartling charges a month ago.\nLABOR DAY BOUT.\n(By Associated Press.)\nLOS ANGELES, Cal., Aug. 4.\nLeach Cross and Joe Rivers were\ninatched to meet here on Labor Day.\nCOUNCIL SECURES\n0& ffllCE\nmt mm m mmm\nun m\nCOST OF PUMPING IS DE\nCREASED ACCORDING TO\nNEW CONTACT; OTHER\nViMFUKXANT MATTJiKb\nDecision was made to again con\ntract with the Arizona Power and\nLight Company for water pumping\npurposes, the milk question was given\nconsiderable thought and discussion,\nstreet improvements thoroughly dis\ncussed and a new City Attorney- was\nappointed at a busy session of the\nCity Council in the city hall last\nnight. Several important matters\nwhich originated at previous meet\nings were also given considerable\nairing but none of these matters\nwere concluded.\nWater Power Contract.\nThe matter of signing a contract\nfor the power used in pumping city\nwater from the Del Rio to the city\nreservoir came in for a lengthy and\nhighly interesting discussion. There\nwere several forms of contracts ad\nvanced by the power company to be\nsigned.\nThe water pumping question has\nalways been a bone of contention\nat council meetings especially when\nthe annual contract came around to\nbe signed. Last year when a new\nform of contract was signed it was\nbelieved that a more economical\nmethod had been secured. But at\nlast night's session it developed Jljat\nthis course was even more expensive\nContinued on Parre S\nASSOCIATION\nTON OH\nT\nAT CITIZENS' MEETING IN\nCHAMBER OF COMMERCE\nROOMS FOR PURPOSE OF\nORGANIZING\nEscaping from the nurse who was\nwatching him, John jD'Dpnel, an in\nmate of the Pioneers Home, 11\nfrom-the porch of that- institutionjLt\nan early hour tins morning ano,\nlanding on the rocks .below, sustiaS1\ning injuries that rcsultefun ifii-\nmeous death, WH'cri found,\nabout fifteen flHImcs aftervlBing\nmissed, he was a mass\nbones and internal injuries\nO'Donel had been in the hospital,\nwhere he was under treatment for\nills incident to old age. A man by\nthe name of Daly had been assigned\nto guard the old fellow, but somehow\nor other the sick man gotit of\nbed and walked over the porcii to\nhis death before his absence was discovered.\nThe deceased was admitted to the\nHome, March 4, 1911, from Coconino\ncounty, to which, place he had come\nin 1871 from Yuma. He was an old\nsoldier and mule driver. He was\nborn in Gahvay, Ireland, in 1831 and\nwas aged 82 years at the time of his\ntragic death. Coroner McLane was\nsummoned. 3\nREPUBLICANS AND DEMO\nCRATS FENCE. OVER THE\nBUSINESS OUTLOOK AND\nPRESENT PROSPERITY\nEM\nTonight's the night when the true\nattitude of Prescott's business men\ntowards the advent of the Northern\nArizona Fair Association and its\npurpose, an annual fair in this city\nwill be made manifest. The Chamber\nof Commerce, pioneer in the move\nment, has issued a general call to\nOF REFUGEES\nEL PASO, Tex., Aug. 4. Suit\nwas instituted today to secure the\nrelease of two hundred and thirty\none Mexican Federals held at Fort\nBliss by habeas corpus .proceedings\nin the United States District Court\nat Austin. The Mexicans were ar\nrested at Naco and Nogalcs, Ariz.\nevery Prescott business man to at-'\nthree months ago.\ntend tonights citizens meeting in\nthe Chamber of Commerce head-j\nquarters.\nTo date, practically the fair prop- j\nosition has tftfcWin the hands of a\nBy Associated Press.\nWASHINGTON, D. C, Aug. 4.\nThe Democrats and Republicans of\nthe Senate fenced over prosperity\nand the business outlook and dis\ncussed the woolen schedules of the\ntariff bill at length, but made some\nprogress today on the metal schedule.\nSenator Stone of Missouri read\ninto the record quotations from the\nmanufacturers and merchants stating\nthe industrial outlook was very fx\nvorable. Senator Gal.linger expressed\nthe assurance that the present pros\nperity was due to Republican poli\ncies and not the coming Democratic\nlaws.\nsenator .Myers ot Montana, in a\nlengthy analysis of the wool schedule\ndeclared the people in his part of\nthe West favored free raw wool, and\nthat a century of protection had\nfailed utterly to add to the wool in\ndustry of this country.\nFAIL TO ATTEND\nE\nCONFER\nBy Associated Press.\nWASHINGTON, D, C, Aug. 4.\nFailure of the Democratic members\nof the House banking and currency\ncommittee to attend the conference\ncalled for today prevented final ac\ntion on the administration currency\nbill. Another conference was called\nfor tomorrow.\nfew industrious -and citizen-members\nof the '\"QfiS'jifijer of Commerce. It\nis now intended to start at once and\nmake the scope more general. Each\ncitizt'jf'j'Ajted, io become a mem-\nbe duly 'lawueUfefctegMafiHlfrct-\n\"k. It Is proposed at this session to\nelect a president, one of the five\nvice-presidents, secretary and treas\nurer. A tentative program has been\nprepared and it is quite likely that\nthe date for the fair will be de\ntermined at this time.\nAfter much persuasion by his fel\nlow members on the committee, R.\nN. Fredericks, one of the most en\nthusiastic figures in the movement,\nhas been prevailed upon to accept\nthe post of president. Mr. Fredericks\nwas the unanimous choice of the\ncommittee. He has affiliated him\nself with the proposition in such an\nenthusiastic and business-like man\nner that there was practically no\nhesitation evinced regarding a\nunanimous choice for the high honor.\nThe post means work and a great\ndeal of it. Mr. Fredericks intends\nto dig right in with tonight's ses\nsion and makes things hum to the\nbest of his ability and energy.\nMISS THEIR MARK.\nOMAHA, Aug. 4. Some unknown\nperson fired two shots through a\nwindow in an unsuccessful attempt\nto assassinate Chief of Detectives\nStephen Maloncy. Maloney, who\nwas sitting in his office at the police\nstation, was unhurt, although the two\nbullets came very close to him.\nMILLIONAIRE'S WILL.\nNEW YORK, Aug. 4. The will of\nAnthony N. Brady, the traction mag\nnate, leaves the liulk of his $70,\n000,000 estate to his five children\nand one grandchild. The widow re\nceived $1,000,000 outright and an an\nnuity of $60,000. One hundred thou\nsand dollars goes to charity.\nWILSON REVEAL\nMEXJl POLICY\nAccepts Resignation of Ambassador\nWilson and Sends Former Governer\nJohn Lind as His Personal Rep\nresentative to Troubled Country\nOut tti Militia\nH\nm\nop Jf lckers Dtrike Jsesuits\nOf Four, Two of Whom are\nLiounty- Officials\nKilling\nBy Associated PressT j\nWHEATLAND, Cal:, Aug. 4.\nWith six companies of militia camped\nin the school grounds, and the hop\npickers' encampment on the Durst\nBrothers ranch reduced to a few\nhundred persons, there is little in\ndication tonight of the rioting which\nbrought death yesterday to four men,\namong them District Attorney.\ni. .Manweii, ot Yuba county. CUtf.\nhop pickers, numberJngYcstertfy\ntwo thousand at Harvesters' camp\";\narc leaving on every train. Adjutant\nGeneral Forbes, the personal rep\nresentative of the Governor, doei\nnot anticipate further trouble. Gen\neral Forbes said tonight the soldfcii\nwill probably be withdrawn tomo\nrow. No ill feeling toward\nguardsmen is displayed by the hop\npickers. The soldiers are being used\nonly to capture William Beck,\ncharged with doing the shooting;\nSunday. A skirmish lfne was thrown;\naround the group pickers until the\nChief of Police of Marysville made\nthe arrest. Beck made no resistance.\nThe authorities say they have one\nthat Beck fired\nic pistol at Man\nheriff Riordon is\nWjyc. been killed by a bullet\n'adtSi-rfatic Ralph H. Durst.\nlefltwners of thejandwho\neain every cne\nagreed\nmmmmtt tjir\nMa\n(ci-aas)? tfjouble, tomghfcisaue\nfStatcnjent. He saysjfc had\nr-.Kjuaiiy to all uemafliiiiexceDt the\nwmsm get\nrrr umior Tiir.Rnta mi\nuuum nuuoc 4- nruu mm\nLOOKED \"INTO I CATTLE\nNEED OF A\nGRAND JURY COMMITTEE\nINTERVIEWS SUPERVIS\nORS\" relativeo Prop\nosition? MAY ADJOURN\nTODAY\nBy Associated Press.\nWASHINGTON, D. C, Aug. 4.\nPresident Wilson took the first steps\ntoday in the policy through which\nhe proposes to deal with the Mexican\nsituation. He formally accepted the\nresignation of Ambassador Henry\nLane Wilson, to take effect October\nI4th, and sent to Mexico as his per\nsonal representative, not as accredited\nto the Hucrta government, former\nGovernor John Lind of Minnesota, a\nlife-long friend of Secretary Bryan.\nThe understanding is that when a\nstable government is established in\nMexico, Lind will be named as Am\nbassador. Mr. and Mrs. Lind de\nparted tonight.\nThe President is said to be ob\nserving with keen interest the efforts\nof leading Mexicans to make peace\nbut will offer no suggestions until\ntheir efforts prove futile. That Lind\nwill be empowered to explain to all\ninquirers the unalterable opposition\nof the American government to the-\n(recognition of the Huerta adminis\ntration, is expected to be a factor\nthat may assist in the situation.\nIn the meantime, arms and muni\ntions of war from the United States\nwill continue to be denied to the\nwarring factions and unless the ap\nparent efforts at peace fail,- the\nUnited States will not act as a\nmediator Lind will undoubtedly act\nin that capacity when the time\ncomes. Lind is a lawyer by pro\nfession, was a Republican while in\nCongress but was elected Governor\non the Democratic ticket and was\ndefeated for re-election. He went\nto Congress again as a Democrat.\nAmbassador Wilson made no com\nment. While the officials of the adminis\ntration look with disfavor upon the\nprocesses of armed revolution to\noverthrow constituted governments\nin Latin-America, there is distinct\nfeeling of sympathy manifest toward\nthe liberal movement in Central\nAmerica, of which Madero's admin\nistration was the beginning in\nMexico-\nGrand jury proceedings entered a\ndifferent channel of action during\nthe third day of its sitting. Inquiries\ninto one killing and two other shoot\ning cases occupied the center of the\nstage during practically all of the\nfirst two clays.\nYesterday after considering several\nodds and ends, cases of minor im\nportance, the inquisitorial body di-\nided into several branch committees\nnd invaded dificifiit sections of the\ncounty building?\"' Ihc tour of in\nformation lasted -forfuU; two hours\nduring the afternoon, after which,\nadjournment took place at about\n3 o'clock. Gambling inv .Prescott,\ncontrary to the..sta?u.te, was. the sub-\niecPi-'UD. for consideration in the\nfnv5jpg. and a large number of\nwitnc3STs-\"was quizzed.\nBelief that the jury would deliver\nits final report yesterday and adjourn\npermanently, was shattered, when at\nS o'clock the twenty-one men and\nthe County Attorney filed out of\nthe secret chamber into the plaza in\nstead of the court room. It is be\nlieved, however, that today will be\nthe last day of the present grand\njury.\nThe feature of the day's proceed\nings was practically conducted in ht\nopen, when six of the grand jury\nmen waited upon the Board of\nSupervisors in their office and in\nquired into the present condition of\nthe court house and the feasibility\nof erecting a new structure to take\nits place. The Supervisors who\nwere in regular monthly session, re\nplied to numerous questions put to\nthem by the grand jurymen which\ntended to a general conclusion of\n\"You can do as you please about it\".\nOne of the Supervisors remarked\nthat there was no especial danger\nof the building caving in over their\nheads. Another declared that the\nonly urgent reason he could summon\nfor advocating a new county court\nhouse was because the records in\npractically every office were not\nprotected in the least against fire.\nCommittees paid visits to the of\nfices of the County School Superin\ntendent, County Recorder, Assessor,\nJustice of the Peace McLane, Tax\nCollector and the Sheriffs offices\nand county jail. Others scattered\nabout the city to investigate the\nsituation there. It is understood that\nsome decidedly interesting reports\nwere rendered after the grand jury\nreconvened.\nUntil yesterday at S o'clock, just\nLIVESTOCK OWNERS ARE\nEXPORTING THROUGH\nSONORA AND DOUGLAS\nPORT OF ENTRY j.\n(By Associated Press)\nDOUGLAS, Aug. 4. Large herds\nof cattle from Chihuahua ranches\narc moving into Sonora to be export\ned from Agua Prieta through the\nDouglas port of entry. The ranchers\nsay it is impossible to export through\nTexas and New Mexico as Chihuahua,\nports are held by the Federals. This\ngives the Insurgent Sonora govern\nment the benefit of the duties on\nstock from Chihuahua, which is\npractically controlled by the Federals.\nTwo thousand heajjS from the Luis\nTerranzajirjinches JjJTChihuafcuaj-ar-rived\ntoday'i'Aguar' Prieta- tpfctfe\nportation atPhls port and moreSje\non the way.\nWOMJORTS\nREFUSE TO\nSURRENDER\nSHANGHAI, China, Aug. 4.\nShots were exchanged between gov\nernment cruisers and the Wusun\nforts held by the Rebels, but with\nout result. Negotiations for the sur\nrender of the forts proved futile.\nseventy-six subpocnacs had been is\nsued by the Court Clerk's office\nand served by the Sheriff's force.\nThe latest batch- was issued as late\nas 3 o'clock yesterday afternoon.\nThe Sheriffs office up until that\ntime had not been instructed to\nI make any arrests from the grand jury\nroom, nor was any partial report\ndelivered.\nWhen the grand jury convened\nfor the day, the members \"filed into\nthe court room. Judge Smith asked\nwhether! the inquisitorial body had\nany report to deliver. Contrary to\nexpectations, the answer was that a\npoint of information was required.\nThe query was whether character\nevidence should be permitted before\nthe grand jury in any form? Judge\nSmith, in replying, called attention\nto his charge in which he said that\nthe grand jury was empowered tp do\nanything along that line but it was\nnot wholly proper to admit such\nevidence as suggested.","height":"26288","width":"18312"}}
